post_text:
Section XI Athletic Council had decided to delay the beginning of sports to January 4, 2021.

This was a difficult decision to make, however, the first and foremost importance is to have a safe and healthy learning environment for our students.

We are hopeful that with time will come an opportunity to compete safely without unintended consequences.

I am certain you are as disappointed as I am with this decision, however, we will forge forward and look to have our student-athletes back with their team and coaches in an environment that will be positive for all.

Click here to see the announcement from Section IX. http://www.westhamptonbeach.k12.ny.us/news/article.aspx?id=121925

— Kathleen Masterson, Director of Health, Physical Education & Athletics

post_text:
While the first day of school in Westhampton Beach was like no other due to new COVID-19 restrictions, students’ eyes smiled from above their masks as they were welcomed back by teachers, administrators and staff.

Following health and safety protocols, students were ushered into the district’s buildings to begin a new year of learning. They quickly adapted to new social distancing procedures and expressed excitement as they met their new teachers and received their first school assignments of the year.

“The many months of planning for the reopening of school proved successful,” said Superintendent of Schools Michael Radday. “We are thrilled to have our students back for in-person instruction.”

post_text:
Governor Cuomo has announced that schools are authorized to reopen for in-person learning this fall. The Westhampton Beach School District has developed a Reopening Plan based on guidance from the Centers for Disease Control (CDC), the New York State Department of Health (NYSDOH), and the New York State Education Department (NYSED). The plan includes a variety of risk mitigation strategies designed to help keep students and staff safe. Please see the Reopening Schools page on the District’s website for more information.

We recognize that some students and their family members may have underlying health conditions that prevent them from attending school. We also recognize that some parents may not feel comfortable with having their children return to school for in-person learning during this pandemic. If you wish to opt-out of in-person learning, please complete the electronic form no later than August 18. A link to the form can be found on the Reopening Schools page on the District's website or here: https://forms.gle/4VTc6sKmi1cPEWw98

post_text:
Westhampton Beach High School students Sophie Cline and Jaden Jacino were named winners in the 18th annual Teeny Awards for the part they played in their school’s production of “Murder on the Orient Express.”

The announcement was made during a virtual ceremony streamed live from the Westhampton Beach PAC on July 23.

The Teeny Awards program recognizes student talent across 18 East End school districts.

The Westhampton Beach School District had a total of five students named as Teeny Award nominees:

Josh Kaplan, Lead Male in a Play
Sophie Cline, Lead Female in a Play
Molly Brennan, Supporting Female in a Play
Olivia Galway, Outstanding Performer in a Play or Musical
Jaden Jacino, Outstanding Poster Design
